== Albert the Macaque ==

Another key part of the investigation is the experimental subject, a monkey ([http://purl.org/obo/owl/NCBITaxon#NCBITaxon_9542 Macaca fuscata]) we will call &quot;Albert&quot;. Like the investigators, Albert has a role — a [http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/OBI_0000097 study subject role]. Albert also has a [http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/UBERON_0001873 caudate nucleus], which is part of his brain. [http://www.obofoundry.org/ro/ro.owl#located_in Located in] his caudate nucleus is a particular neuron we will call &quot;X123&quot;. X123 is the neuron that has its activity measured by the assay. There is also a stimulus — a flash of light — that is presented to Albert. Albert [http://www.obofoundry.org/ro/ro.owl#participates_in participates in] this stimulus, which is an instance of an OBI [http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/OBI_0000807 presentation of stimulus].

== Single Unit Recorder #15 ==

Also important for the investigation is the device used to make the measurement of the neural activation. &quot;Single unit recorder #15&quot; is a particular [http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/OBI_0000832 measurement device]. It has its own function — to measure neural activity — which is an instance of the class of [http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/OBI_0000453 measure function]s. Each time single unit recorder #15 is used to measure the activity of neuron X123 there is a record of its output, called a &quot;spike train&quot;. The spike train is an instance of a [http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000109 measurement datum].

