= Relations =

Hopefully much of the discussion of the particulars of this case will seem sensible. However it's likely that some of it sounds unnecessary and redundant. For example, why have a protocol, an objective, a plan, and a planned process for each of the parts of the study design? Even the names of some of the relations between these things may sound peculiar.

In order to understand these peculiarities we have to look at the Basic Formal Ontology ([http://ifomis.org/bfo BFO]) that is the foundation for OBI. BFO is the &quot;upper level&quot; ontology that all of the ontologies in the [http://obofoundry.org OBO Foundry] share. While OBI and the other OBO ontologies have been developed by looking at cases of scientific practice, BFO is based on a long tradition of philosophy that is the source of the word &quot;ontology&quot;. Ontology (as a branch of philosophy) is about understanding the basic categories of things in the world. But since these categories are so basic to our everyday thinking and language, it's difficult to avoid hidden assumptions and avoid &quot;stretching&quot; the meaning of everyday words. Like any science, ontology involves some difficult concepts and has its own jargon.

This difficulty can be justified by the utility of ontology. Biomedical informatics is one good example. To program a computer properly we have to express our categories and assumptions with painful clarity. Ontology has turned out to be very useful for programming computers to reason properly in science and other domains. A short discussion of the BFO classes and relations will help to sort out the peculiarities of the model of the Lauwereyns 2002 investigation.

We've already seen the distinction between particulars and classes (or universals). For our purposes here, the main relation that holds between classes is the [http://purl.org/obo/owl/OBO_REL#is_a is a] or sub-class relation. The most general class in OBI is [http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.1#Entity entity] — every particular is an entity. OBI borrows its most general classes, such as [http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.1#Entity entity], from BFO. All the other OBO ontologies also use BFO and this helps to coordinate them.

BFO entities are divided into [http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.1/snap#Continuant continuant]s and [http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.1/span#Occurrent occurrent]s. Occurrents are the kinds of things that have a beginning, a middle, and an end, such as processes and periods of time: the life of Julius Caesar, the hour of his death. Continuants are things that persist through time, and that undergo processes: Julius Caesar himself, the color his skin, his role as Roman general.

The most important occurrent for our purposes is the process (&quot;[http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.1/span#ProcessualEntity processual entity]&quot;). Processes have participants — continuants that [http://www.obofoundry.org/ro/ro.owl#participates_in participate in] the process. OBI focuses on [http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/OBI_0000011 planned process]es, which are processes that [http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/OBI_0000308 realize] a [http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/OBI_0000260 plan]. Many planned processes have a [http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/OBI_0000293 specified input] and a [http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/OBI_0000299 specified output] that are specified by the plan.

Continuants are divided into [http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.1/snap#DependentContinuant dependent continuant]s, [http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.1/snap#IndependentContinuant independent continuant]s, and [http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.1/snap#SpatialRegion spatial region]s. Independent continuants exist by themselves, and the main class of these in OBI is [http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.1/snap#MaterialEntity material entity]. Material entities include natural things such as [http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/PR_000000001 protein]s, [http://purl.org/obo/owl/CL#CL_0000000 cell]s, [http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/OBI_0100026 organism]s, and [http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/OBI_0000181 population]s, and [http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/OBI_0000047 processed material]s such as [http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/OBI_0100060 cell culture]s and [http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/OBI_0000968 device]s.

Dependent continuants can't exist without some independent continuant. A dependent continuant [http://purl.org/obo/owl/OBO_REL#inheres_in inheres in] an independent continuant, and conversely the independent continuant is the [http://purl.org/obo/owl/OBO_REL#bearer_of bearer of] the dependent continuant. There are [http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.1/snap#SpecificallyDependentContinuant specifically dependent continuant]s that inhere in a single independent continuant instance, and there are [http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.1/snap#GenericallyDependentContinuant generically dependent continuant]s that can be made concrete by many different independent continuant instances. The specific ones include [http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.1/snap#Quality qualities] and [http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.1/snap#RealizableEntity realizable entities] such as [http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.1/snap#Disposition disposition]s, [http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.1/snap#Function function]s, [http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.1/snap#Role role]s, and [http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/OBI_0000260 plan]s. Albert's study subject role (a dependent continuant) inheres in Albert (an independent continuant), and conversely he is the bearer of that role.

The most important type of generically independent continuant for OBI is the [http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000030 information content entity] class. Information content entities are generically ''dependent'' because they always depend on ''some'' independent entity, but ''generically'' dependent because there can be many copies. For example, the spike trail that is generated by the first assay in L2002 can be made concrete by multiple computer files or paper printouts.

In order for the OBI model of an investigation to work we have to get the classes of the particulars right. Once we know the classes it's often easy to see what the relations have to be. The main relation that holds between a particular and a universal is [http://purl.org/obo/owl/OBO_REL#instance_of instantiation]. A specifically dependent continuant [http://purl.org/obo/owl/OBO_REL#inheres_in inheres in] an independent continuant. A generically dependent continuant [http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/OBI_0000297 is concretized as] an independent continuant. An independent continuant can [http://www.obofoundry.org/ro/ro.owl#participates_in participate in] a process. A [http://www.ifomis.org/bfo/1.1/snap#RealizableEntity realizable entity] (a disposition, function, role, or plan) can be [http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/OBI_0000308 realized] by a process. Both occurrents and continuants can [http://www.obofoundry.org/ro/ro.owl#has_part have parts].

Plans are an interesting case. A protocol is an information entity, perhaps a list of steps. It has a part which is the objective specification — a bit of information that specifies the objective of the protocol. Since protocols are information, they are generically dependent and must be made concrete as something. In this case the protocol is made concrete as a plan in the mind of an investigator, or perhaps in the running software of a robot. The plan is a specifically dependent realizable entity that gets realized by a planned process. And the planned process has a special relation to the objective specification: [http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/OBI_0000417 achieves planned objective].

= Conclusions =

OBI can successfully model the Lauwereyns 2002 investigation with a fair degree of detail. More detail is possible, and some of the steps of the investigation have been left out here, such as the surgery to implant the electrodes, the protocol for the care of the monkeys, and the process of inference from the result data to the conclusions of the report. Much repetitive detail has also been omitted: there were two monkeys and many trials with different stimuli. Computers are good at handling such large sets of similar data, but our purpose here has been to explain the OBI model to human beings who want to apply it.

